{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/bowel-screening/background-information/why-screen/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"59ee19d7-4ba3-578e-b3cd-847e1a4f2924","slug":"why-screen","fullItemName":"Why screen?","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 53ef3d40-7e4f-4cb1-ab90-d421b2dc6be2 --><h2>Why screen for bowel cancer?</h2><!-- end field 53ef3d40-7e4f-4cb1-ab90-d421b2dc6be2 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 64eb6044-d258-453a-a024-d0ba2c7cbf9f --><!-- begin field 76f793d9-2a33-433d-8167-7174ad623d13 --><ul><li><strong>Bowel cancer is the fourth most common cancer in the UK.</strong><ul><li>In 2015, 41,804 new cases were diagnosed [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">Cancer Research UK, 2019a</a>]:<ul><li>34,729 in England — age standardised incidence rate 69.4 per 100,000.</li><li>3,695 in Scotland — age standardised incidence rate 72.4 per 100,000.</li><li>2,259  in Wales — age standardised incidence rate 71.8 per 100,000.</li><li>1,121 in Northern Ireland — age standardised incidence rate 72.6 per 100,000.</li><li>55% of cases were male and 45% female.</li></ul></li><li>In 2016 there were 16,384 deaths from bowel cancer in the UK — it is the second most common cause of cancer death in the UK [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">UK National Screening Committee, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">Cancer Research UK, 2019a</a>].</li><li>The risk of developing bowel cancer increases with age.<ul><li>Around 80% of people diagnosed with bowel cancer are aged over 60 years [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">UK National Screening Committee, 2018</a>].</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>The NHS Bowel Cancer Screening Program was introduced in 2006 with the aim of identifying bowel cancer at an early stage when treatment is more likely to be successful.</strong><ul><li>The 5-year survival rate following diagnosis of bowel cancer is 59% — survival is strongly related to stage at diagnosis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">Cancer Research UK, 2019a</a>].</li><li>The 5-year survival rate can be improved from 7% for a metastatic cancer at diagnosis to 93% for a bowel cancer detected early at Dukes’ stage A [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">UK NSC, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">NHS Health Scotland, 2017</a>].</li><li>In addition to identifying cancers earlier, screening can also reduce the incidence of bowel cancer by endoscopic removal of pre-malignant lesions at colonoscopy.</li></ul></li><li>Regular bowel cancer screening has been shown to reduce the risk of dying from bowel cancer by over 16% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">UK NSC, 2016</a>].</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">UK NSC, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">Koo, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bowel-screening/references/\">Bowel Screening Wales, 2019a</a>]</p><!-- end field 76f793d9-2a33-433d-8167-7174ad623d13 --><!-- end item 64eb6044-d258-453a-a024-d0ba2c7cbf9f -->","topic":{"id":"3ce0939c-7050-5776-a27a-f61be0cde1ee","topicId":"82504955-0e84-433e-bad4-93b1ed97ce03","topicName":"Bowel screening","slug":"bowel-screening","lastRevised":"Last revised in May 2019","chapters":[{"id":"bc2d7627-8fa0-5266-9a00-e712c6e2d181","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"ab7b5b81-4eeb-53d8-a024-9a25103a6bb9","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"b6c6aff8-902e-5f92-9bcc-c86051bf35e9","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"5a4a85ce-0817-5737-a4bd-b21e5f4d471d","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"e84f94a1-b8f1-52c2-89c5-fe98e969d445","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"f993604e-d9e1-5f3d-a163-a694e0eec778","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"31c9b8f0-2cc3-51a8-8121-02bedaa57461","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"82451698-7794-505f-b671-4e02d8d0007c","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"33e248f5-b211-5eca-9cdf-aff8271e67a6","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"43e1bbb7-2cd7-5327-a858-4aa44aaa9a47","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"97919224-16db-5c80-b944-2c004d2a0911","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"54e92059-64bb-5834-a997-d84f4e68b93b","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"00cf5ee9-8702-5df0-adb4-3e4698cfeaab","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"59ee19d7-4ba3-578e-b3cd-847e1a4f2924","slug":"why-screen","fullItemName":"Why screen?"},{"id":"f6d55026-a5f9-5644-a9fa-4134537e2911","slug":"potential-harms-with-screening","fullItemName":"Potential harms with screening"},{"id":"7ca2fbab-3ac6-5abd-a4c5-3c550333af98","slug":"screening-tests","fullItemName":"Screening tests"},{"id":"17acab04-e959-570d-bbaf-6eb7c85f5fef","slug":"screening-outcomes","fullItemName":"Screening outcomes"},{"id":"5345e798-40b6-53a4-8819-972c2d4bbc2d","slug":"the-nhs-bowel-screening-programme","fullItemName":"The NHS Bowel scr